    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-12-05T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-12-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="1463"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1463">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">125.953/12–549: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Second Secretary of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bacon</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-12-05">December 5,
                            1949.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 5—1:44 p. m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2543. Following is Tsingtao’s 50, December 5 (reEmbtel 2536 to Department
                    December 4<note n="25" xml:id="d1463fn25">Not printed.</note>): <quote
                        rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Your 91, 2nd. All foreigners must now depart China from Shanghai.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Embassy gathers from this and preceding telegrams from Tsingtao that residents
                    Tsingtao are obliged proceed Shanghai and cannot obtain permits for exit at
                    Tsingtao or via Tientsin.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 2543, repeated Taipei 108, Hong Kong telCan 842.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bacon</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
